'''Bochasanwasi Akshar Purushottam Sanstha''' ('''BAPS''') ([[IAST]]: ''{{IAST|Bocāsanvāsī Akshar Purushottam Sansthā}}''), is a [[Hindu]] religious and social organization within the [[Swaminarayan faith|Swaminarayan branch of Hinduism]]. BAPS was established on 5 June 1907 by [[Shastriji Maharaj]] after leaving the [[Laxmi Narayan Dev Gadi|Vadtal Gadi]] of the [[Swaminarayan Sampraday]].  It was formed on the founder's interpretation that [[Swaminarayan]] was to remain present on earth through a lineage of [[Guru|Gunatit Gurus]] or [[Akshar Purushottam Upasana|Akshar]] dating all the way back to [[Gunatitanand Swami]] -  one of Swaminarayan's prominent devotees.<ref name="Williams2001">{{cite book|title=An Introduction to Swaminarayan Hinduism|last=Williams|first=Raymond|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2001|isbn=0-521-65279-0|location=New York|pages=106|via=}}</ref>{{rp|55}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rinehart|first1=Robin|title=Contemporary Hinduism: Ritual, Culture, and Practice|date=2004|publisher=Library of Congress|isbn=1-57607-905-8|page=215}}</ref> [[Gunatitanand Swami]] was succeeded by [[Bhagatji Maharaj]], [[Shastriji Maharaj]], [[Yogiji Maharaj]], [[Pramukh Swami Maharaj]] and [[Mahant Swami Maharaj]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.baps.org/Announcement/2016/Final-Darshan-and-Rites-of-Pramukh-Swami-Maharaj-9961.aspx|title=Final Darshan and Rites of Pramukh Swami Maharaj|website=BAPS Swaminarayan Sanstha|access-date=2016-08-13}}</ref> Due to the organizational emphasis on the [[Akshar Purushottam Upasana|Akshar Purushottam]] doctrine, it essentially forms the organization's middle name. The fundamental beliefs of BAPS include the spiritual guidance through the living Akshar or Guru who is believed to have attained oneness with Swaminarayan. [[Mahant Swami Maharaj]] is the current Guru and the president of the organization.

As a global well established [[Hindu]] organization, BAPS actively engages in a range of endeavors aimed at spirituality, character-building, and human welfare. The activities span religious, cultural, social, and humanitarian domains.  Through these activities, it aims to preserve Indian culture, ideals of [[Hinduism|Hindu faith]], family unity, selfless service, interfaith harmony and peaceful coexistence. 55,000 volunteers and 3,300 temples serve 3,300 communities around the world. As of August 2018 the BAPS has approximately 1,560 saints or Sadhus, among the most saints in one sanstha in Hinduism. 

As part of its efforts towards community outreach, BAPS also engages in a host of humanitarian and charitable endeavors, by which its volunteers serve neighbors and communities.  Through the BAPS Charities [[nonprofit organization|non-profit aid organization]], With total assets valued approximately at 2.23 lakh crore INR roughly 30.7 billion USD in 2018 the BAPS has spearheaded a number of projects around the world in the arenas of healthcare, education, environmental causes, and community-building campaigns.

==Mandirs==
[[File:DSC09917 BAPS Temple - E view by Volkan Yuksel.jpg|300px|left|thumb|[[BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir Atlanta|BAPS Swaminarayan Mandir]] [[Atlanta]]]]
The [[mandir]], known as a [[Hindu]] place of worship, serves as a hub for the spiritual, cultural, and humanitarian activities of BAPS. The organization has about 1,300 mandirs and a total of 3,300 volunteer-run centers spanning five continents.<ref name="BAPS Global Network Site">{{cite web|title=BAPS Center Locator|url=http://www.baps.org/Global-Network.aspx|publisher=BAPS Swaminarayan Sanstha|accessdate=12 December 2012}}</ref><ref name="BAPS Swaminarayan Sanstha">{{cite web|title=92nd Birthday Celebrations of Pramukh Swami Maharaj, Ahmedabad, India|url=http://www.baps.org/News/2012/92nd-Birthday-Celebrations-of-Pramukh-Swami-Maharaj-4404.aspx|publisher=BAPS Swaminarayan Sanstha|accessdate=17 February 2013}}</ref>  In the tradition of the [[Bhakti Movement]], [[Swaminarayan]] and his spiritual successors began erecting mandirs to provide a means to uphold proper devotion to God on the path towards [[moksha]], or ultimate liberation.<ref name="Gadhada II-27">{{cite book|last=Gadhada II-27|title=The Vachanamrut: Spiritual Discourses of Bhagwan Swaminarayan|year=2001|publisher=Swaminarayan Aksharpith|location=Amdavad|isbn=81-7526-190-0}}</ref>{{rp|440}} BAPS mandirs thus facilitate devotional commitment to the [[Akshar Purushottam Upasana]], in which followers strive to reach the spiritually perfect state of Aksharbrahman, or the ideal devotee, thereby gaining the ability to properly worship Purushottam, the Supreme Godhead.<ref name="Kim PT">{{cite journal |last=Kim |first=Hanna |title=Public engagement and personal desires: BAPS Swaminarayan temples and their contribution to the discourses on religion |journal=International Journal of Hindu Studies |date=December 2009 |volume=13 |issue=3 |doi=10.1007/s11407-010-9081-4 }}</ref>{{rp|7–13}}

===Mandir Rituals===
The offering of [[bhakti]], or devotion to God, remains at the center of mandir activities. In all BAPS Swaminarayan mandirs, [[murtis]], or sacred images of [[Swaminarayan]], [[Gunatitanand Swami]], BAPS guru's and other deities, are enshrined in the [[Garbhagriha|inner sanctum]]. After completion of [[prana pratishta]] or life-force installation ceremonies, the deities are believed to reside in the murtis, and are thus subjects of direct worship through sacred daily rituals.<ref name="Williams2001"/>{{rp|240}} In many mandirs, murtis are adorned with clothes and ornaments and devotees come to perform [[Darśana|darshan]], the act of worshiping the deity by viewing the sacred image.<ref name="Williams2001"/>{{rp|131, 140}}<ref name="EoH 119">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Constance|title=Encyclopedia of Hinduism|year=2007|publisher=Infobase Publishing|location=New York|isbn=0-8160-7336-8|pages=119}}</ref> [[Aarti]], which is a ritual of waving lit lamps in circular motions to illuminate the different parts of the murti while singing a song of praise, is performed five times daily in [[Shikharband Mandir|shikharbaddha mandirs]] and twice daily in smaller [[Dev Mandir|mandirs]]. Additionally, food is offered to the murtis amidst the singing of devotional songs three times a day as part of the ritual of [[Prasad|thaal]], and the sanctified food is then distributed to devotees.<ref name="Williams2001"/>{{rp|140}}  Daily readings of and discourses on various Hindu scriptures also take place in the mandir.<ref name="Williams2001"/>{{rp|132}}  Many mandirs are also home to BAPS sadhus, or  monks.<ref name="Williams2001"/>{{rp|50}}  On weekends, assemblies are held in which sadhus and devotees deliver discourses on a variety of spiritual topics. During these assemblies, bhakti is offered in the form of call-and-response hymns (''[[kirtans]]'') with traditional musical accompaniment. Religious assemblies also take place for children and teenagers of various age ranges.<ref name="Williams2001"/>{{rp|62}}  Throughout the year, mandirs celebrate traditional Hindu festivals. Assemblies with special discourses, kirtans, and other performances are arranged to commemorate [[Swaminarayan Jayanti|Rama Navami]], [[Janmashtami]], [[Diwali]], and other major Hindu holidays.<ref name="Williams2001"/>{{rp|138–147}} Members of the sect are known as [[Satsangi]]es.  Male Satsangies are generally initiated by obtaining a [[Kanthi Mala|kanthi]] at the hands of a sadhu or senior male devotee while females receive the [[vartman]] from the senior women followers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.swaminarayan.org/faq/bapsgeneral.htm#4 |title=Q#4 How does a person join the Swaminarayan Sampraday? |work=FAQ|publisher=swaminarayan.org}}</ref>

===Mandir Activities===
In addition to being focal points of religious activity, BAPS mandirs are also centers of culture.<ref name="Kim PT"/>{{rp|21}}  Many forms of traditional Indian art have their roots in Hindu scriptures and have been preserved and flourished in the setting of mandirs.<ref name="Williams2001"/>{{rp|220}}  Many BAPS mandirs outside of India hold [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] classes to facilitate scriptural study, instruction in traditional dance forms in preparation for performances in festival assemblies, and music classes where students are taught how to play traditional instruments such as [[tabla]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Shri Swaminarayan Mandir|url=http://pluralism.org/profiles/view/71207|work=Pluralism Project|publisher=Harvard University|accessdate=11 January 2013}}</ref><ref name="Indiapost Harijayanti">{{cite news|title=BAPS celebrates Swaminarayan Jayanti & Ram Navmi|url=http://www.indiapost.com/baps-celebrates-swaminarayan-jayanti-ram-navmi/|accessdate=11 January 2013|newspaper=India Post|date=22 April 2011}}</ref>  Many devotees view the mandir as a place for transmission of knowledge of Hindu values and their incorporation into daily routines, family life, and careers.<ref name="BS">{{cite book|last=Kim|first=Hanna|title=Being Swarninarayan: the ontology and significance of belief in the construction of a Gujarati diaspora|year=2001|publisher=Bell & Howell Information and Learning Company |location=Ann Arbor}}</ref>{{rp|418–422}}<ref name="India Herald Spiritual Quotient">{{cite news|title=1,200 young adults from North America attend Spiritual Quotient Seminar|url=http://india-herald.com/young-adults-from-north-america-attend-spiritual-quotient-seminar-p2299-1.htm|accessdate=11 January 2013|newspaper=India Herald|date=30 June 2010}}</ref>

Apart from classes teaching about religion and culture, mandirs are also the site of activities focused on youth development. Many centers organize college preparatory classes, leadership training seminars and workplace skills development workshops.<ref name="Atlanta Conf">{{cite news|last=Dave|first=Hiral|title=Baps tells Youth to uphold values|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/world/report_baps-tells-youth-to-uphold-values_1232640|accessdate=11 January 2013|newspaper=Daily News & Analysis|date=20 February 2009}}</ref><ref name="Kalam Youth">{{cite news|title=Strive to be unique, Kalam tells youth|url=http://www.indiapost.com/strive-to-be-unique-kalam-tells-youth/|accessdate=11 January 2013|newspaper=India Post|date=29 April 2011}}</ref><ref name="Chino Hills Youth">{{cite web|last=Patel|first=Divyesh|title=BAPS Commemorates Education with Educational Development Day|url=http://www.chinohills.com/news-articles-details/BAPS_Commemorates_Education_with_Educational_Development_Day-1542|work=ChinoHills.com|accessdate=11 January 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130222020011/http://www.chinohills.com/news-articles-details/BAPS_Commemorates_Education_with_Educational_Development_Day-1542|archivedate=22 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Many centers host women's conferences aimed at empowering young women.<ref name="Chicago Women's">{{cite news|last=Padmanabhan|first=R|title=BAPS Swaminarayan Sanstha Hosts Women's Conference in Chicago|url=http://www.nritoday.net/women/287-aug-08-baps-swaminarayan-sanstha-hosts-womens-conference-in-chicago|accessdate=11 January 2013|newspaper=NRI Today|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130916133018/http://www.nritoday.net/women/287-aug-08-baps-swaminarayan-sanstha-hosts-womens-conference-in-chicago|archivedate=16 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  They also host sports tournaments and initiatives to promote healthy lifestyles among children and youth.<ref name="Childrens Health">{{cite news|last=Piccirilli|first=Amanda|title=BAPS Charities stresses importance of children's health|url=http://www.timesherald.com/article/20120813/NEWS03/120819840/baps-charities-stresses-importance-of-children-146-s-health|accessdate=11 January 2013|newspaper=The Times Herald|date=13 August 2012}}</ref>  Many centers also host parenting seminars, marriage counseling, and events for family bonding.<ref name="Hinduism Today Parenting">{{cite web|title=Parents Are the Key|url=http://www.hinduismtoday.com/modules/smartsection/print.php?itemid=1432|publisher=Hinduism Today|accessdate=11 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=BAPS Charities|url=http://berkleycenter.georgetown.edu/resources/organizations/baps-charities|publisher=Georgetown University|accessdate=11 January 2013}}</ref>

BAPS mandirs and cultural centers serve as hubs of several humanitarian activities powered by local volunteers. Mandirs in the US and UK host an annual walkathon to raise funds for local charities such as hospitals or schools.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rajda|first=K|title=Local communities join BAPS Walkathon|url=http://www.indiapost.com/local-communities-join-baps-walkathon|accessdate=11 January 2013|newspaper=IndiaPost|date=29 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=BAPS Charities Hosts 15th Annual Walkathon|url=http://www.indiawest.com/news/4867-baps-charities-hosts-15th-annual-walkathon.html|accessdate=11 January 2013|newspaper=India West|date=6 June 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608222818/http://www.indiawest.com/news/4867-baps-charities-hosts-15th-annual-walkathon.html|archivedate=8 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=BAPS Charities Host Community Walk in Support of American Diabetes Association and Stafford MSD Education Fund|url=http://www.indoamerican-news.com/archives/7136|accessdate=11 January 2013|newspaper=Indo American News}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  Many centers also host annual health fairs where needy members of the community can undergo health screenings and consultations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gibson|first=Michael|title=BAPS Charities Health Fair 2012|url=http://www.nbcdfw.com/on-air/community/BAPS-Charities-Health-Fair-2012-165775856.html|publisher=NBCUniversal|accessdate=11 January 2013}}</ref>  During weekend assemblies, physicians are periodically invited to speak on various aspects of preventative medicine and to raise awareness on common conditions.<ref>{{cite web|last=Patel|first=Divyesh|title=BAPS Charities to Hold Women's FREE Health Awareness Lectures 2010 on Saturday, June 5th 2010|url=http://www.chinohills.com/news-articles-details/BAPS_Charities_to_Hold_Womens_FREE_Health_Awareness_Lectures_2010_on_Saturday_June_5th_2010_-1343|work=ChinoHills.com|accessdate=11 January 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130728033711/http://www.chinohills.com/news-articles-details/BAPS_Charities_to_Hold_Womens_FREE_Health_Awareness_Lectures_2010_on_Saturday_June_5th_2010_-1343|archivedate=28 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In times of disaster, centers closest to the affected area become hubs for relief activity ranging from providing meals to reconstructing communities.<ref>{{cite news|title=BAPS Care International launches relief efforts for Hurricane Katrina victims|url=http://india-herald.com/baps-care-international-launches-relief-efforts-for-hurricane-katrina-victi-p801-1.htm|accessdate=11 January 2013|newspaper=India Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=BAPS Charities helps victims of tornadoes|url=http://www.indiapost.com/baps-charities-helps-victims-of-tornadoes/|accessdate=11 January 2013|newspaper=IndiaPost|date=20 May 2011}}</ref>

===Notable Mandirs===
