===Health===
To prevent and alleviate bodily suffering and to foster good health and physical well-being, [[BAPS Charities]] engages in numerous health-focused activities. The organization operates 16 hospitals and clinics serving over 600,000 people annually, with its most recent hospitals opening in [[Ahmedabad]] in 2012 and in [[Vadodara]] in 2013.<ref name="Clarke 2011 43"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Narendra Modi inaugurates BAPS Yogiji Maharaj Hospital in Ahmedabad|url=http://deshgujarat.com/2012/05/17/narendra-modi-inaugurates-baps-yogiji-maharaj-hospital-in-ahmedabad/|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=DeshGujarat|date=17 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Inauguration of BAPS Shastriji Maharaj Hospital, Atladra (Vadodara), India|url=http://www.baps.org/News/2013/Inauguration-of-BAPS-Shastriji-Maharaj-Hospital-4664.aspx|publisher=Swaminarayan Aksharpith|accessdate=29 March 2013}}</ref>  Additionally, BAPS Charities organizes health fairs run by volunteer medical professionals where visitors can undergo screening tests, increase health awareness, participate in consultations, and receive treatment.<ref>{{cite news|title=BAPS Annual Health Fair Promotes Wellness|url=http://www.indoamerican-news.com/archives/1901|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=Indo American News|date=22 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Patel|first=Sandip|title=BAPS Health Fair in Bartlett a big success|url=http://www.indiapost.com/baps-health-fair-in-bartlett-a-big-success/|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=India Post|date=16 May 2011}}</ref>  Supporting the goals of [[Michelle Obama]]'s "[[Let's Move]]" campaign which is working to end childhood obesity, BAPS Charities recently launched a health awareness initiative in the United States focused on educating parents and children on benefits of a vegetarian diet.<ref>{{cite news|title=BAPS Charities support Michelle Obama's initiative|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/154507/baps-charities-support-michelle-obamas.html|accessdate=21 March 2013|newspaper=Deccan Herald|date=18 April 2012}}</ref>  To support biomedical research, the Toronto chapter of BAPS Charities donated $100,000 raised from walk-a-thons for Toronto's [[Hospital for Sick Children]]'s Research and Learning Tower Campaign.<ref name=":0">{{cite web|title = Support SickKids with BAPS Charities annual walk|url = http://www.insidetoronto.com/news-story/67954-support-sickkids-with-baps-charities-annual-walk/|work = InsideToronto.com|accessdate = 21 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{cite web|title = Annual Report 2010-2011|url = http://www.sickkidsfoundation.com/togive/downloads/SKF_Annual_Report_1011.pdf|publisher = SickKids Foundation|accessdate = 21 March 2013}}</ref> In India, the organization has carried out anti-addiction campaigns led by several thousand children who spent their summer vacations traveling through cities and villages persuading people to give up their addictions with personal appeals and presentations on the dangers of addictive behaviors.<ref name="Clarke 2011 44">{{cite book|last=Clarke|first=Matthew|title=Development and Religion: Theology and Practice|year=2011|publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing|location=Northampton, MA|isbn=978-1-84844-584-0|page=44}}</ref>

===Education===
With a goal of improving educational opportunities and outcomes for younger generations, [[BAPS Charities]] funds scholarships, operates 10 schools and 8 colleges in addition to supporting other schools and running hostels.<ref>{{cite book|last=Clarke|first=Matthew|title=Development and Religion: Theology and Practice|year=2011|publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing|location=Northampton, MA|isbn=978-1-84844-584-0|pages=44–45}}</ref>  Through volunteer-led classes, the organization is working towards achieving 100 percent literacy in villages in India.<ref name="Clarke 2011 44"/>  In Africa, BAPS Charities has been active in providing children in need with school uniforms, school supplies, and food and in addition to helping improve school facilities.<ref>{{cite web|title=BAPS Charities helps school children in Durban|url=http://www.bapscharities.org/mediacenter/announcements/2008/darbanschool.htm|publisher=BAPS Charities|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=BAPS Charities Food Drive, Dar-es-Salaam|url=http://www.bapscharities.org/mediacenter/announcements/2010/daressalaamfood.htm|publisher=BAPS Charities|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=BAPS Charities helps school students facing water-crisis|url=http://www.bapscharities.org/mediacenter/announcements/2009/watercrisis.htm|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>  In North America, BAPS Charities also organizes annual seminars for professional development where workshops help youth develop interpersonal skills, public speaking, management skills.<ref>{{cite news|title=BAPS Swaminarayan Sanstha holds National Youth Leadership Seminar|url=http://www.atlantadunia.com/dunia/News09/N411.htm|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=Atlanta Dunia}}</ref>

===Environment===
[[BAPS Charities]] manages several programs designed to protect and improve the environment. Volunteers across the world have raised ecological awareness and promoted conservation by employing energy-efficient technologies and organizing large-scale tree planting campaigns and recycling programs.<ref>{{cite news|title=BAPS Charities Goes Green for Earth Day|url=http://www.atlantadunia.com/dunia/News09/N2011/N628.htm|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=Atlanta Dunia|date=23 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=BAPS Charities goes green for Earth Day|url=http://www.indiapost.com/baps-charities-goes-green-for-earth-day/|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=India Post|date=5 May 2012}}</ref>  In India, the organization also leads campaigns to improve water supply and conservation and arranges camps to teach better animal husbandry.<ref>{{cite book|last=Clarke|first=Matthew|title=Development and Religion: Theology and Practice|year=2011|publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing|location=Northampton, MA|isbn=978-1-84844-584-0|page=45}}</ref>  In Gujarat, BAPS along with other religious sects, professional associations, and civil rights groups expressed support for the Sardar Sarovar Dam project in the 1990s, citing its prospect of generating hydropower, irrigation, potable water, and flood management.<ref name="Jones 2005 8890">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Lindsay|title=Encyclopedia of Religion|year=2005|publisher=Thomson Gale|location=Farmington Hills|isbn=0-02-865984-8|page=8890}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Unprecedented Awakening to Counter the Challenge of the anti-Narmada Protestors [Narmada samena padkaro jheeli leva lokoman abhootpurva chetna]|newspaper=Gujarat Samachar|date=29 December 1990}}</ref>   Although some groups criticized the project for its effect of displacing area residents, BAPS sponsored initiatives to relocate and aid the affected communities.<ref name="Jones 2005 8890"/>

===Disaster relief===
Relieving human suffering in times of humanitarian emergencies remains an important component of [[BAPS Charities]]’ work. Within hours after the [[2001 Gujarat earthquake]], BAPS volunteers began providing victims with daily hot meals, clean water, and clothing and assisted with debris removal and search and rescue missions; the organization also adopted more than 10 villages in which they rebuilt the entire community, including all infrastructure and thousands of earthquake-resistant homes.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Malik|first=Rajiv|title=To Rebuild Kutch|journal=Hinduism Today|date=July–August 2001|url=http://www.hinduismtoday.com/modules/smartsection/item.php?itemid=4063|accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Prince Charles comes to the aid of quake victims |url=http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/news/ie/daily/20010307/iin07011.html |accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=Indian Express|date=6 March 2001}}</ref>  With the help of donations from volunteers in India and abroad, the organization helped rebuild the area's communities by constructing schools, hospitals, and other buildings.<ref>{{cite news|title=Post-quake Kutch schools get facelift|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2002-06-22/ahmedabad/27318762_1_school-buildings-anjar-kutch|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=22 June 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Harley|first=Gail|title=Hindu and Sikh Faiths in America|year=2003|publisher=Shoreline Publishing|location=New York|isbn=0-8160-4987-4|pages=82–83}}</ref> After [[Hurricane Katrina]] struck the United States Gulf Coast region, BAPS Charities volunteer teams supplied hot food, water, emergency supplies, and relocation aid for victims.<ref>{{cite news|title=BAPS gives $10,000 to student victims of Katrina|url=http://india-herald.com/baps-gives-to-student-victims-of-katrina-p816-1.htm|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=India Herald}}</ref>  The organization partnered with [[UNICEF]] to provide medicine, clean water, and temporary housing for children affected by the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news|title=BAPS Charities’ donation totals $63,000 to UNICEF  for Haiti Earthquake Relief Fund|url=http://www.atlantadunia.com/dunia/News09/N561.htm|accessdate=6 March 2013|newspaper=Atlanta Dunia|date=6 August 2010}}</ref>

===Community===
