{{Infobox Website | name = Eroakirkosta.fi | favicon = | logo = | screenshot = | caption = | url = {{URL|http://eroakirkosta.fi/}} | commercial = | type = | registration = | owner = | author = | launch date = 2003 | current status = Active | revenue = | slogan = }}
'''Eroakirkosta.fi''' is a [[Finland|Finnish]] website which offers an electronic service for resigning from Finland's [[state church]]es; the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church of Finland]] and the [[Finnish Orthodox Church]]. "Eroa kirkosta" translates to "resign from the church".
The website was created by [[Freethinkers of Tampere]], an organisation that supports a formal [[separation of church and state]], and opened on 21 November 2003. The Finnish law on [[freedom of religion]] was updated on 1 August 2003 and then allowed resigning from religions without a visit to a bureau. Because eroakirkosta.fi is not maintained by [[magistrate]]s, the website can not directly resign a person from a church. Instead, the website forwards the filled-in resignation forms to magistrates who then complete the resignation. Resignations through [[e-mail]] are allowed because the Finnish law requires resignations to be "in writing" but not "[[Signature|signed]]". Eroakirkosta.fi also gives the user the alternative to print the resignation form and send it through regular [[mail]].
Eroakirkosta.fi became popular very quickly. Within ten weeks over 1,400 people had resigned through the website.<ref>{{cite web | title=Kirkosta eroaminen suosittua internetin kautta | work=Digitoday | url=http://www.digitoday.fi/viihde/2004/02/20/Kirkosta+eroaminen+suosittua+internetin+kautta/20047759/66 | accessdate=2007-10-20 | language=Finnish}}</ref> In 2004, almost 39% of all resignations in the country were done through eroakirkosta.fi. In 2005, the percentage increased to 68.9. In 2006, almost four out of five persons resigned through the website. The total resignation rates in Finland have also increased. The number of people resigning from the state churches has tripled in six years (2000&ndash;2006),<ref>{{cite web | title=Kirkosta eronneiden määrä kolminkertaistunut kuudessa vuodessa | work=[[Etelä-Suomen Sanomat]] | url=http://www.ess.fi/Article.jsp?article=157028&main=-1&dept=1 | accessdate=2007-10-20 | language=Finnish}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> and the 2005 and 2006 resignation numbers both break the old record of 30,710 from 1992.<ref>{{cite web | title=Kirkosta erottiin ennätystahtiin | work=[[MTV3]] | url=http://www.mtv3.fi/uutiset/kotimaa.shtml/arkistot/kotimaa/2006/01/417269 | accessdate=2007-10-20 | language=Finnish}}</ref> 47 300 members left the church through the service in 2008, that is 91% of all resignations (52,200).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eroakirkosta.fi/media/none/tiedote4_09.html?year=2009 |title=Valtionkirkosta erosi ennätysmäärä jäseniä |publisher=Eroakirkosta.fi |date=2009-02-16 |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref> In 2011, 46,502 resignations and in 2012, 41,261 resignations were registered at the Eroakirkosta.fi site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eroakirkosta.fi/static/ek-tilastot/ |title=tilastot |publisher=Eroakirkosta.fi |date= |accessdate=2013-09-28}}</ref>
== Publicity == The web service received publicity October 2010, after a gay rights panel discussion on [[YLE TV2|TV]] on 12 October was followed by thousands of people resigning from the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church of Finland|Evangelical Lutheran Church]] by using the service.<ref>{{cite web | author=Helsingin Sanomat International Edition | title=Up to 18,000 leave Lutheran Church over statements on gay current affairs programme | date=18 October 2010 | url=http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Up+to+18000+leave+Lutheran+Church+over+statements+on+gay+current+affairs+programme/1135260979317 | accessdate=19 October 2010 }}</ref>
