'''Half-widow''' is a term given to [[Kashmiri people|Kashmiri]] women whose husbands have [[Forced disappearance|disappeared]] and were still missing during the [[Kashmir conflict|ongoing conflict]] in [[Kashmir]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/the-other-half/|title=The other half: For many Kashmir ‘half-widows’, the remarriage ruling means little|date=2 March 2014|work=The Indian Express}}</ref> These women are called "half-widows" because they have no idea whether their husbands are dead or alive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-24530201|title=In pictures: Kashmir's 'half-widows'|work=BBC World News}}</ref>
Thousands of husbands in Kashmir disappeared during the conflict. .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2013/09/dilemma-kashmir-half-widows-201392715575877378.html|title=The dilemma of Kashmir's half-widows}}</ref>
Most of the half-widows have not remarried due to doubt about their husband's fate and a lack of consensus among [[Muslim scholars]] on the issue. In Kashmir, a group of religious scholars issued a [[fatwa]] on the 26 of December 2013 saying that half-widows are allowed to remarry after a waiting period of four years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ummahhelpline.com/qa/291.php|title=Issue of remarrying of kashmari HALF-WIDOWS? -UmmahHelpline|work=ummahhelpline.com}}</ref>
