[[Image:John-William-Brodie-Innes.jpg|thumb|right|John William Brodie-Innes]]
'''John William Brodie-Innes''' ( 10 March 1848 – 8 December 1923 ) was a leading member of the [[Hermetic Order of the Golden Dawn]]'s Amen-Ra Temple in [[Edinburgh]].

J.W. Brodie- Innes was born at Downe in Kent,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://libindx.moray.gov.uk/subjects/subject_people_report_view.asp?REF_ID%3DNM011538 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-09-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140908155056/http://libindx.moray.gov.uk/subjects/subject_people_report_view.asp?REF_ID=NM011538 |archivedate= 8 September 2014 |df= }}</ref> where his Scottish born father Rev. [[John Brodie Innes]] ( 1815-1894 ) had been Vicar from 1846. His father was a friend and confidant of a neighbour at Downe, [[Charles Darwin]]. A lawyer by profession, he was a member of the Sette of Odde Volumes ( a London bibliophile society ), and was its president in 1911. He wrote several novels on witchcraft and magic and is believed to have been one of [[Dion Fortune]]'s occult teachers. (Fortune was also taught by such occult practitioners as [[Moina Mathers]] and Dr Theodore Moriarty).

Throughout the dissensions of the Golden Dawn, Brodie-Innes remained loyal to [[Samuel Liddell MacGregor Mathers|MacGregor Mathers]], and on the death of his chief in 1918 published an affectionate obituary titled "MacGregor Mathers - Some Personal Reminiscences"<ref>( {{cite web|url=http://www.esotericgoldendawn.com/tradition_macgregorreminiscences.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101123190959/http://esotericgoldendawn.com/tradition_macgregorreminiscences.htm |archivedate=23 November 2010 |df= }} ) - Article reprinted from ''[[The Occult Review]]'', Vol. 29, No. 5 ( May 1919 ), pp. 284-286.</ref> in the May 1919 issue of ''[[The Occult Review]]''.

