{{Refimprove|date=December 2014}} {{Infobox ancient site |name = Lucus Feroniae |native_name = |alternate_name = |image = LucusFeroniaeForumbase.jpg |alt = |caption = View of the archaeological site of Lucus Feroniae |map_type = Italy Lazio |map_alt = |location = [[Lazio]], [[Italy]] |region = Provincia di Roma |type = Settlement |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = |abandoned = |epochs = [[Roman Republic]] [[Roman Empire]] |cultures = [[Ancient Rome]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = yes |archaeologists = |condition = |ownership = |management = |public_access = yes |website = |notes = }}
'''Lucus Feroniae''' was an ancient [[sacred grove]] (''"[[lucus]]"'') dedicated to the [[Sabine]] goddess [[Feronia (mythology)|Feronia]]. It was located in [[Etruria]], across the ancient [[Via Tiberina]], in what is now the territory of the modern commune of [[Capena]], [[Lazio]], next to the border with the neighbouring comune of [[Fiano Romano]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/413184 |title=Places: 413184 (Lucus Feroniae) |author=Harris, W., DARMC, R. Talbert, S. Gillies, T. Elliott, J. Becker |accessdate=December 18, 2014 <!-- 2:56 pm --> |publisher=Pleiades}}</ref>
It was visited both by [[Latins (Italic tribe)|Latins]] and [[Sabines]] even in the time of [[Tullus Hostilius]] and was plundered by [[Hannibal]] in 211 BCE. In [[Roman Empire|Imperial]] times it became an independent community receiving a colony of [[Augustus|Octavian]]'s veterans (''Colonia Iulia felix Lucoferensis'') and possessing an [[amphitheatre]], capable of housing up to 5,000 spectators, a [[basilica]], a forum, baths and numerous other edifices. See ''[[Feronia (Etruria)]].
A museum houses parts of statues, some of them with interchangeable hands and heads, depending from the current emperor ruling.
[[File:LucusFeroniaeAmphitheatre.jpg|thumb|Roman amphitheater of Lucus Feroniae]]
The villa of the Volusii Saturnini is located nearby.<ref name="Marzano2007">{{cite book|author=[[Annalisa Marzano]]|title=Roman Villas in Central Italy: A Social and Economic History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hSUsb6Gf5KgC&pg=PA181|year=2007|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-16037-X|pages=181–}}</ref><ref name="Goodman2006">{{cite book|author=Penelope Goodman|title=The Roman City and Its Periphery: From Rome to Gaul|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MM5_AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA52|date=7 November 2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-30335-9|pages=52–}}</ref><ref>http://www.etruriameridionale.beniculturali.it/index.php?it/188/descrizione</ref>
